Chapter 1: Preparing the data

1.1: Describing the data

For our dataset, we chose a dataset from the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO) on all recorded aviation accidents between January 2008 and May 2022. Aviation accidents are defined in the dataset as incidents which resulted in serious damage, injury or even fatality. The dataset contains 25 variables on a total of 6109 observations. A few of the more important variables are: (a) number of fatalities in the accident, (b) country where the accident occured, (c) the flight phase during which the accident happened (e.g., landing, taxi, etc.), (d) the type of aircraft involved and (e) the year of occurrence. Important to note also is that the dataset suffers from missing data. The proportion of missingness varies per variable, ranging from 77% (StateOfOperator) to 4% (Model).

data<-read.csv(file="Data/ICAO_accidents.csv",header = T)

1.2: Organising the data and summary statistics

Before we start exploring the data, it is important to clean the dataset up first. To start, we decided to remove the variables stated below due to them either containing duplicate information (e.g., Date and Year) or due to having information that we deemed too specific for our current endeavour (e.g., the name of the operator of the aircraft).
Variables: Location, Model, Registration, Operator, StateOfOperator, StateOfRegistry, Class, ScheduledCommercial, TypeDesignator, Official, OccCats Besides removing these variables, we also merged a few combinations of variables. Firstly, the two weight variables (Over2250 & Over5700) were merged to create one categorical weight variable (WeightCat). Secondly, the two binary variables Airplane and Helicopter were merged to create one AircraftType variable. Thirdly, we grouped Risk variable into RiskCat based on ICAO Cathegory organizaton. Please note that beside these large changes small changes were also applied (e.g., missing data classified as Unknown/Undefined). For a more detailed view of the changes, see the comments between the code.

#to limit ourselves 
#remove to specific information and duplicates
data %<>% mutate("AircraftType"=case_when(Airplane=="True"~"Airplane",
                                     Helicopter=="True"~"Helicopter"),
                "WeightCat"=case_when(Over5700=="True"~">5700",
                                        Over2250=="False" ~ "<2250",
                                        Over2250=="True" & Over5700=="False" ~
                                        "2250-5700"),
                "RiskCat"=case_when(Risk %in% c("AMAN","MAC","CFIT","FUEL",
                                                'GTOW',"LOC-I","LOLI","LALT",
                                                "UIMC")~"Airborne",
                                    Risk %in% c("F-NI","SCF-NP","SCF-PP",
                                                "SCF")~"Aircraft" ,
                                    Risk %in% c("EVAC","FPOST","GCOL","RAMP",
                                                "LOCG","RE","RIA","RIVAP")~
                                                "Ground Operations",
                                    Risk %in% c("CABIN","EXTL","OTHR","OTH",
                                                "SEC","GS","OD")~"Miscellaneous",
                                    #wrongly codded "unk" spotted and added
                                    Risk %in% c("Unknown","UNK","unk")~
                                                "Unknown/Undefined",
                                    Risk %in% c("RS")~"Runway Safety",
                                    Risk %in% c("BIRD","WILD")~"Wildlife",
                                    Risk %in% c("ADRM","ATM")~
                                              "Non-aircraft-related",
                                    Risk %in% c("ARC","CTOL","USOS")~
                                              "Takeoff and Landing",
                                    #wrongly codded "TURB" spotted and added
                                    Risk %in% c("ICE","TURB","WSTRW","TUBR")~
                                      "Weather", 
                                  Risk %in% c("MED")~"Injuries of Persons")) %>% 
  #fill NA with 'Unknown' tag
  mutate(RiskCat= replace_na(RiskCat, "Multiple"),
         WeightCat=replace_na(WeightCat,"Unknown") )%>% 
  #select variables of interest 
  select(!c("Location","Operator","Date","Model","StateOfOperator","Class",
            "ScheduledCommercial","Official","OccCats","Over2250","Over5700",
            "Helicopter","Airplane","Registration","X","StateOfRegistry",
            "StateOfOccurrence")) %>% 
  #change character variables into factors
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor) 
#levels vith no tag to be changen to "Unknown"
levels(data$Risk)[1]<-"Unknown"
levels(data$FlightPhase)[1]<-"Unknown"
levels(data$InjuryLevel)[1]<-"Unknown"

After these actions, the following variables were left to be used further in our exploratory data analysis:

  • StateOfOccurrence: the country of occurrence

  • FlightPhase: the flight phase of occurrence (take off, landing, approach, etc.)

  • Fatalities: the number of fatal victims

  • WeightCat: a categorical aircraft basic operational weight (categories are: less than 2250KG, between 2250KG and 5700KG, over 5700KG)

  • InjuryLevel: the level of injuries on people involved in the occurrence

  • AircraftType: whether the aircraft was an airplane or a helicopter Engine: the number of engines in the aircraft

  • EngineType: the aircraft engine type (categories are: jet, turboprop or piston)

  • Risk: the main risk type involved in the occurrence, coded according to High Risk Categories as used by the ICAO Year: the year of occurrence RiskCat: the main risk type involved in the occurence, coded according to High Risks Categories codes used by the ICAO

The distribution of number of fatalities was very skewed and consisted of 62% zeros (see Table 2), indicating no deaths during the accident. Additionally there was a large proportion (19%) of missing values. Among the fatal accidents, the number of deaths were most frequently between 1 and 25 (Figure 1) with median = 2. However, there are many individual accidents with the number of victims ranging from 25 to 300.

#proportion of 0 fatalities and missing values
data %>% 
  subset(Fatalities==0 | is.na(data$Fatalities)) %>% 
  mutate(Fatalities= case_when(Fatalities==0 ~ "0",
                               is.na(Fatalities)~ "Missing"
                               )) %>% 
  group_by(Fatalities) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            prop= round(n/nrow(data), digits=2))%>%
  kableone(., format = "html",
    caption = 
    c("Table 2. Number of fatalities: proportion of 0 and missing values"))

Chapter 2: Exploratory data analysis

For our exploratory data analysis, we wanted to investigate the following three questions:

  1. Does the number of accidents seem to change over time?

  2. During which flight phase do the most accidents seem to occur?

  3. What are the risk types associated with fatal and non-fatal accidents?

2.1: Accidents over time

To investigate the number of accidents over time, we created the following plots that show the amount of accidents over time per type of aircraft in different parameterizations of accident: (a) total death count, (b) accident count and (c) fatal accident count.

#death count per year- trend
data %>% filter(Fatalities >0) %>% group_by(Year,AircraftType) %>% 
  summarise(sum=sum(Fatalities)) %>% ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=sum,color=AircraftType)) + 
  geom_line(size=1)  + scale_color_brewer(palette="Set1")+
  labs(x = "Year", y="Number of deaths",color="Aircraft Type")+ ggtitle("The total death count over time")+theme_minimal()

Figure 7 and 8 look at the relation between flightphase and weight categories respectively and the proportion of accidents per year. Figure 7 shows that the proportion of accidents per flightphase are quite consistent over the years. The latter plot, however, does show that in 2012, there was a much lower proportion of accidents in the lowest weight category, and a much higher proportion of accidents in the highest weight category compared to 2010 and 2011. This could be indicative that there were less issues with lower weight aircrafts and thus fewer accidents. However, important to note is that this could also be confounded by the number of flights per aircraft. Confirmatory research would be necessary for proper conclusions.

2.2: Exploring fatality

2.2.1: How frequent are fatal accidents compared to the other Injury Level categories?

To investigate the fatality of aircraft accidents, we made the following plot (see Figure 9) which shows that one fifth of all aircraft accidents result in a fatal injury.

#Proportion of accidents that occurred per injury level
data  %>%

2.2.3: Fatality by flight phase

Since we want to focus more on the differences between fatal and non-fatal accidents, from now on we categorise InjuryLevel as: Fatal, Non-Fatal (None, Minor, Serious combined) and Unknown. Then, we explored fatality in even more depth by looking at during which flight stages the most accidents occur proportionally per aircraft. The plot below, Figure 11, shows that for helicopters, most accidents tend to happen en route for both fatal and non-fatal accidents. Interesting to note is that for airplanes, fatal accidents also happen most often en route. Non-fatal accidents, however, seem to happen most often during the landing phase.

#order of the FlightPhase factor with decreasing frequency of occurrence(for airplanes)

2.2.4: Fatality and risk categories

Focusing on the main reasons for the aircraft accidents, we grouped Risk variable onto 12 categories and saved under RiskCat variable. In the Figure 12 we can see the main reason of non-fatal accidents involving airplanes and helicopters. The main cause of non-fatal accident for airplanes is connected to Runway safety hazards(accidents happening due to poor preparation of the runway), which is directly connected to Landing and Take-off flying phases and is in line with previous part of analysis. For helicopters the the mixture of at least 2 hazards coming from different categories listed in RiskCat is the cause of accidents. Figure 13 represents risks involved in fatal accidents. It shows that the most frequent cause of catastrophes among airplanes are connected to Airborne hazards(accidents that happens in the flying phase).An example of this would be a air crush with other flying object.On the other hand, for helicopters causes classified under Airborne and Multiple categories are the major reasons for the accidents. We could conclude that among fatal accidents in general Airborne hazards are the main cause. Also helicopters catastrophes more often involve several causes in comparison to the airplanes.
